t‘‘Robbed of Half a Million,’’ Harper’s Monthly (October 1866) -- t‘‘In the ‘Libey’,’’ Harper’sWeekly (20 February 1864) -- t‘‘Mr.Williamson Slippey and His Salt,’’ New Eclectic Monthly (October 1870) -- t1864 -- t‘‘A Night on the Mississippi,’’ Putnam’s (April 1870) -- t‘‘Mrs. Spriggins, the Neutral,’’ Southern Magazine (February 1871) -- t‘‘Buried Alive,’’ Harper’sWeekly (7 May 1864) -- t‘‘A Night in the Wilderness,’’ Galaxy (May 1871) -- t‘‘The Freedman’s Story,’’ Harper’s Monthly (October 1866) -- t‘‘Road-Side Story,’’ LandWe Love (August 1866) -- t1865 -- t‘‘The Skeleton in the Closet,’’ Galaxy (June 1866) -- t‘‘Sentenced and Shot,’’ Lakeside Monthly (November 1870) -- t‘‘Wilhelmina,’’ Atlantic Monthly (January 1875) -- tAftermath -- t‘‘A True Story, RepeatedWord for Word As I Heard It,’’ Atlantic Monthly (November 1874) -- tAuthor Sketches -- tIllustration Sources -- tCivilWar Glossary -- tBibliographic Essay -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEven before the first cannonballs were fired at Fort Sumter, American writers were trying to make creative sense of the War Between the States. These thirty-one stories were culled from hundreds that circulated in popular magazines between 1861 and the celebration of the American centennial in 1876. Arranged to echo the sequence of the unfolding drama of the war and Reconstruction, together these short stories constitute an “inadvertent novel,” a collective narrative about a domestic crisis that was still ongoing as the stories were being written and published.The authors, who include Louisa May Alcott and Mark Twain, depict the horrors of the battlefield, the suffering in prison camps and field hospitals, and the privations of the home front. In these pages, bushwhackers carry the war to out-of-the-way homesteads, spies work households from the inside, journeying paymasters rely on the kindness of border women, and soldiers turn out to be girls. The stories are populated with nurses, officers, speculators, preachers, slaves, and black troops, and they take place in cities, along the frontier, and on battlefields from Shiloh to Gettysburg.The book opens with a prewar vigilante attack on the Underground Railroad and a Kansas parson in Henry King’s “The Cabin at Pharoah’s Ford” and concludes with an ex-slave recalling the loss of her remaining son in Twain’s “A True Story.” In between are stories written by both women and men that were published in magazines from the South and West as well as the culturally dominant Northeast. Wartime wood engravings highlight the text. Kathleen Diffley’s introduction provides literary and historical background, and her commentary introduces readers to magazine authors as well as the deepening disruptions of a country at war.Just as they did for nineteenth-century readers, these stories will bring the war home to contemporary readers, giving shape to a crisis that rocked the nation then and continues to haunt it now.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony19th century. 0aWar stories, American. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aAlcott, Louisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClemens, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoulson, G, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCulver, J, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Rebecca, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiffley, Kathleen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGray, Confederate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrimes, Charity, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1